\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script shows important information about the active MIDI take, selected notes, and selected CCs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script can open a separate GUI window, or can be docked in the marker/region lanes of the MIDI editor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script improves on REAPER's native Properties windows in several ways:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The GUI is continuously updated and does not interfere with MIDI editing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If multiple events are selected, value ranges are shown.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Note, CC and take information are all shown simultaneously.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Note and CC positions can be displayed in any of REAPER's time formats.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab In Measure:Beat:Ticks format, script can display fractional tick values.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When working with multiple MIDI editors, the script will automatically switch to the active editor.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 GUI FONTS AND COLORS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the script's USER AREA the user can change fonts and colors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The piano roll font settings can also be accessed through the right-click context menu.\line Font options are BLUR, SHADOW, INVERT, NATIVE, BOTTOMUP, MONO, VERTICAL and OUTLINE. NOTE: On Windows, small LICE text is not properly antialiased. The "BLUR" option may achieve a similar effect by slightly blurring the text.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 TERMINATION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If all MIDI editors are closed, the script will continue running in the background (with negligible CPU usage), and will automatiically reappear when a new editor is opened.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To terminate the script, the user must explicitly close the GUI window, or click the toolbar button again (or equivalently, run the script action again). The first time that the script is closed by clicking the toolbar button, REAPER will ask whether to terminate the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the GUI window is open:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Click on any of the highlighted values to open a Properties window or a dropdown menu in which the values can be changed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The default colors of the GUI, as well as the font size, can be customized in the script's USER AREA.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When opening, the script will recall its last-used position and size.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the Inspector is docked in the marker/region lanes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Right-click on the Inspector to open a context menu.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 FLICKERING ON WINDOWS OS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On WindowsOS, graphics that are drawn inside REAPER's windows by scripts (for example by the Multi Tool, or when the MIDI Inspector is docked) may occasionally flicker. This flickering can be reduced by limiting the refresh rate of the window, but the optimal setting is specific to each DAW and may depend on factors such as CPU speed and monitor refresh rate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the right-click context menu, the user can enable or disable flickering reduction, and select a refresh rate.\line 0.05 seconds is the default, and should work fine on most systems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 WARNING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Updating MIDI information in realtime can take a toll on the responsiveness of the MIDI editor, particularly if the take contains many thousands of MIDI events. The GUI therefore provides a "Pause" option, which will pause the realtime updating.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Also, the user can set the minimum wait time between updating the inspector.\line To do so, edit the "updateTime" parameter in the script's USER AREA.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Lua script for warping the positions or values of MIDI CCs and velocities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Warp axis:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Events positions can be warped horizontally (to the left or right), and event values can be warp vertically (up or down).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When warping events in multiple lanes together, or events that do not have values, such as text or sysex, warping can only be horizontal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Warp direction is determined by initial mouse movement: To warp event positions horizontally, move the mouse left/right when the script starts; to warp event values vertically, move the mouse up/down. (This is similar to how REAPER's own "move in one direction only" mouse modifiers work.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Applications:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Changing a linear ramp into a parabolic (or other power) curve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Accelerating a series of evenly spaced notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Changing the curve shape of LFOs.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Single lane vs all lanes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned inside a CC lane (or inside the notes area) when the script starts, the script will only warp selected events in that single lane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a lane divider (or in the ruler area) when the script starts, the script will warp all selected events in all lanes together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or the Actions list (or, actually anywhere outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and can then be run by the "js_Run the mouse editing script that is armed in toolbar" script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script can apply two different acceleration curves: smooth or steep:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The mouse middle button can be used to switch between the curves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Both of the curves are invertible, so events that were warped can later be re-selected and re-warped back to their original positions.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 js_Mouse editing scripts can be controlled by the mouse and keyboard while the script is running: * Mouse movement: Changes the extent of warping * Mouse left click: Terminates the script. * Mouse middle click: Toggle the warp curve shape. * Mouse right click: While right button is down, temporarily warp in both directions. * Mousewheel: -- (not used by this script) * Any keystroke: Terminates the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key (Ctrl/Cmnd, Alt, Shift or Win) while theh script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 1: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Lua script for warping and stretching the positions of MIDI CCs and notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script only affects events in the MIDI editor lane under the mouse cursor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for changing a linear CC ramp into more complex logistic-type curves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for accelerating and decelerating a series of evenly spaced notes, as is typical in a trill.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Select MIDI events to be warped (the script works on any CCs, notes, text or sysex events).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Position mouse in lane, {\i within} the time range of the selected events. (Events to left and right of mouse position will be stretch separately.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab Press the shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab Move mouse left or right to stretch the corresponding side, or move mouse up or down to warp towards or away from mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5)\tx360\tab To stop the script, press the shortcut key again, or if the shortcut key has been held down for more than one second, simply lift it.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSEWHEEL AND KEYBAORD CONTROL\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts can be controlled by the mouse and keyboard while the script is running: * Mouse movement: Changes the extent of warping * Mouse left click: Terminates the script. * Mouse middle click: -- (not used by this script) * Mouse right click: -- (not used by this script) * Mousewheel: -- (not used by this script) * Keyboard shortcut (assigned in Actions list): Starts/Terminates the script. * Any keystroke: Terminates the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, \line
using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\line
\line
* Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button,\line
the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key (Ctrl/Cmnd, Alt, Shift or Win) while theh script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a toolbar arming feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The mouse editing scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 1: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and edit takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of edit and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Arch selected CCs or velocities in the lane under mouse towards mouse position, using a linear or power curve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is outside the selected events' PPQ position range, the Arch curve is similar to a Tilt towards the mouse position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The shape of the curve can be changed with the mousewheel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for tweaking an existing, complex CC or velocity curve up or down, without having to re-draw the curve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for quickly applying and auditioning crescendo-decrescendo (fade-in and fade-out) curves.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions, in at least two ways:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Select events to be arched/tilted. (Note that the scripts obeys the MIDI editor's "Edit only active channel" setting.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Position mouse inside the lane. (After the script starts, the mouse may move out of the target lane.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab Start script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab Control script with mouse:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Mouse position determines position to arch towards.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Middle click switches between a linear/power curve and a sine curve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Mousewheel tweaks the curve shape.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 STARTING AND STOPPING THE SCRIPT\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
