{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Practice Coach\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use Reaper when practicing guitar or bass or flute or bagpipe or......whatever you want to practice.\line This reascript will change the practice tempo in 8 steps:\line Step 1 plays with 50% of maxBPM in 5 min\line Step 2 plays with 70% of maxBPM in 2 min\line Step 3 plays with 60% of maxBPM in 2 min\line Step 4 plays with 80% of maxBPM in 2 min\line Step 5 plays with 65% of maxBPM in 2 min\line Step 6 plays with 75% of maxBPM in 2 min\line Step 7 plays with 80% of maxBPM in 2 min\line Step 8 plays with 50% of maxBPM in 3 min\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 How to use:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make a time selection on what you want to practice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Load Practice Coach\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Hit Start button (on script window) and practice along\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If there is no temposign at start of time selection you will be asked if you want to create one, else Practice Coach will load the tempo from sign and start to play time selection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When first step is done Reaper stops\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To contine with step 2 hit Continue (if auto-continue is active - just wait)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab After finishing the 8th step you have practiced different tempos in 15 min and script resets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Is auto-increase selected the temposign will be increased by 1 bpm after finishing.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER does not currently offer the option of displaying thumbnails in video items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Moreover, if thumbnails are extracted and displayed in static empty items, zooming in will result in messy tiling when the items' pixel widths become longer than the width of the thumbnails, while zooming out will result in tiny, barely visible images when the item widths become shorter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script offers a workaround: It runs in the background, and automatically adjusts the width of items containing thumbnail images to the approximate width of the images.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All calculations are performed when zooming, not when scrolling, so the script doesn't interfere with playback or recording.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script will try to detect the optimal W/H ratio from the image in the first thumbnail item in each track. Otherwise, a default 16:9 will be applied.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before running, select all the items that must be auto-adjusted. These may be enpty items, MIDI items, or dedicated video processor items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script can be linked to a toolbar button, which will light up while the script is running.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script creates thumbnail items for selected video items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The thumbnail items are created inside the selected destintaion track, which may be video items' own track, in which case the thumbnails will be drawn over the video items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The items are created at regular spacing along the entire lengths of the video items. The script open a dialog window in which the user can specify the spacing.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On Linux, ffmpeg needs to be installed, and on WindowsOS and macOS, an ffmpeg executable is required.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 High-resolution thumbnails require huge amounts of RAM, so the script can scale thumbnails down to any custom size, which can also be customized in the dialog window.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER does not currently offer the option of displaying thumbnails in video items. This script is the first in a pair of scripts that are intended to remedy the shortcoming:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The second script in the pair is "js_Video - Automatically adjust size of thumbnail items when zooming", which turns static thumbnails into a repsonsive, auto-zooming thumbnail track.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script extracts thumbnail images from selected video items, and displays the thumbnails in selected empty items, MIDI items or dedicated video processor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If multiple selected video items overlap a thumbnail item, a video item on the same track takes precedence, followed by video items in the closest parent folder, and lastly the video item in the highest (i.e. lowest-numbered) track.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Thumbnail items can be added manually at hitpoints, or at any desired regular spacing, for example by creating a long empty item across the entire length of the video item and then splitting at the grid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Alternatively, empty items can be added by the script "mrlimbic_ffprobe scene detect.lua", which creates empty items at scene (or camera/line) cuts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On Linux, ffmpeg needs to be installed, and on WindowsOS and macOS, an ffmpeg executable is required.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 High-resolution thumbnails require huge amounts of RAM, so the script can scale thumbnails down to any custom size. The default size can be specified in the script file's User Area.\line If no default value is set, the script will ask the user to enter a custom value each time that the script runs.\par}
}

